Two paradigms of programming:
1. Imperative: Describing the method and expected result.
2. Descriptive: Describing the expected results but not telling how.

Handling of data is important to formulate an efficient algorithm. 

Data Structures are a particular way of organising primitive data types (int, char etc.) into a fomr of data called abstract data types, which are mathematical models of formulating data.

Way a program works is hidden from the user: encapsulation.

Design patterns are way of describing algorithms and not worrying much about the data form usage. Data types to be used can vary from on situation to another
